# 34_objects_scriptable_smoke — sixth row-bound model Scriptable.
# s230 m1 OPENED the arc (read-side surface, no mutating verbs);
# s231 m2 CONTINUED it by adding two collection-level structural
# verbs (`objects new <type>` / `objects delete <iid>`), which lets
# this smoke gain the same owns-its-conditions BUILD UP / VALIDATE /
# TEAR DOWN structure 33_layers and 27_guides established.
# s232 m3 CONTINUES it by adding five element mutating verbs on the
# proxy: `toggle_visible`, `set_visible <bool>`, `toggle_locked`,
# `set_locked <bool>`, `rename "<name>"`. Each rides
# EditObjectFieldCommand — a new command class added in m3, direct
# analog of EditLayerFieldCommand minus the Color field (scene
# objects don't carry a single colour tag; their colour lives in
# FillStyle/StrokeStyle and is handled by the existing
# EditObjectCommand surface).
#
# Validates the design banked in CANON's "Row-bound model Scriptables —
# collection-as-router with transient per-instance proxies" entry,
# applied for the sixth time to the active document's scene-content
# surface.
#
# Two addressing surfaces, one router:
#
#   objects         — collection. ONE registry entry. Set queries
#                     (count, all_iids) plus invoke-shaped reads
#                     (find_by_name, find_by_type) AND the m2
#                     structural verbs (new, delete).
#   objects.<iid>   — per-instance proxy. NOT in the registry —
#                     materialised on demand, destroyed at end-of-
#                     statement. Element queries (name, type,
#                     visible, locked, parent_iid, child_count, iid)
#                     AND the m3 element mutating verbs (toggle_visible,
#                     set_visible, toggle_locked, set_locked, rename).
#
# The shared `objects` prefix is load-bearing: the router splits a
# dotted token on the first `.`, looks the prefix up in the registry,
# and asks the matched object to resolve the suffix. Collection name
# and proxy prefix MUST be the same string.
#
# ── What s232 m3 changes about this smoke ────────────────────────────────
#
# m2 covered every element QUERY on the proxy. m3 adds the five element
# MUTATING verbs. The smoke gains two new phases:
#
#   Phase 5c — full round-trip exercise of all five mutating verbs on
#              `a` (the Path), including the "no-op same value" and
#              (for rename) "no-op empty arg" short-circuits; plus a
#              cross-check that rename propagates to the find_by_name
#              tree-walk surface, not just the node-local field.
#   Phase 6c — minimal re-exercise of rename + toggle_locked on `b`
#              (the Group), confirming the verbs are type-agnostic
#              (no Path-vs-Group branch hiding in the code path).
#
# Net structural change to the doc: still zero. New, then renamed /
# toggled / locked, then deleted. Side effect on the undo stack now
# includes a handful of EditObjectFieldCommand entries between the
# AddNodeCommand and DeleteObjectCommand bookends.
#
# ── Pre-stated count ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Expected: 25 pass / 0 fail / 0 error.
#
# Breakdown:
#   Phase 4 (cross-Scriptable boundary, carried from m1): 1 assert.
#   Phase 5 (proxy round-trip on `a` after mint as "path"):
#     name == "", type == "path", visible == true, locked == false,
#     child_count == 0                                        → 5 asserts.
#     parent_iid chain — layers.<a_parent> name resolves      → 1 assert.
#   Phase 5c (NEW in m3 — five element mutating verbs on `a`):
#     rename round-trip (rename → no-op-same → no-op-empty)   → 3 asserts.
#     find_by_name cross-check (iid round-trips via variable) → 1 assert.
#     toggle_visible / set_visible round-trip                 → 3 asserts.
#     toggle_locked / set_locked round-trip                   → 3 asserts.
#   Phase 6 (proxy round-trip on `b` after mint as "group"):
#     type == "group", child_count == 0                       → 2 asserts.
#   Phase 6c (NEW in m3 — minimal verbs on `b`):
#     rename → assert name; toggle_locked → assert locked     → 2 asserts.
#   Phase 7 (find_by_type now finds in-scope tokens):
#     find_by_type "path"  result resolves to a path-typed    → 1 assert.
#     find_by_type "group" result resolves to a group-typed   → 1 assert.
#   Phase 8 (count snapshot for end-of-run delta — no assert here):
#     get + set bindings only; the actual count_before equality
#     assert lives in Phase 10 after tear down completes.
#   Phase 9 (cross-Scriptable boundary holds AFTER mint):
#     layers.found_layer name re-asserts the sentinel         → 1 assert.
#     (objects find_by_name on the layer sentinel still ""
#      verified by trace inspection — no literal-RHS-against-
#      bound-variable shape, so trace only.)
#   Phase 10 (tear down + count baseline restoration):
#     objects count == count_before                            → 1 assert.
#
# Total: 1 + 6 + 10 + 2 + 2 + 2 + 1 + 1 = 25.
#
# ── Phases ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
#   1. REGISTRY      — list shows `objects` (visual).
#   2. DISPATCH      — count, all_iids dispatch (visual).
#   3. SCOPE-NEG     — find_by_type on out-of-scope tokens returns ""
#                      (visual).
#   4. SCOPE-POS     — cross-Scriptable boundary assert (carried from
#                      m1): layers find_by_name PASSES on a sentinel-
#                      named test layer; objects find_by_name for the
#                      same string returns "" (visual).
#   5. BUILD UP (a)  — mint `objects new "path"`, bind to `a`, exercise
#                      every element query on `objects.a`.
#   5c. MUTATING (a) — exercise all five m3 mutating verbs on `a`
#                      (rename / toggle_visible / set_visible /
#                      toggle_locked / set_locked), with round-trip
#                      and no-op coverage; cross-check rename via
#                      find_by_name.
#   6. BUILD UP (b)  — mint `objects new "group"`, bind to `b`,
#                      exercise the type-discriminator and the
#                      child_count.
#   6c. MUTATING (b) — minimal rename + toggle_locked on `b` to
#                      confirm the verbs work uniformly across
#                      types.
#   7. find_by_type  — with in-scope objects in the doc, the previously-
#                      empty find_by_type "path" / "group" now return
#                      iids; assert via the proxy that the returned
#                      iid resolves to a node matching the expected
#                      type.
#   8. COUNT DELTA   — count went up by 2 between BUILD UP and tear
#                      down's start; will return to baseline after
#                      tear down. Asserted via a difference variable.
#   9. POST-MINT     — the layers-side cross-Scriptable assert still
#                      holds with `objects` populated — confirms the
#                      router partition isn't shape-sensitive to
#                      content presence in `objects`.
#  10. TEAR DOWN     — `objects delete a` / `objects delete b` /
#                      `layers delete test_layer`. Final `list` shows
#                      `objects` still registered (no transient
#                      `objects.<iid>` entries despite all the proxy
#                      materialisation across this run).

#[sub] === Phase 1: REGISTRY ===
#[sub] `objects` should appear in the registry list. We don't assert
#[sub] on the full list (surrounding entries depend on what else is
#[sub] registered); the trace inspection is the check.

list

#[sub] === Phase 2: DISPATCH — collection queries ===
#[sub] count returns an Int; all_iids returns a String. The dispatch
#[sub] working IS the foundation check; the trace shows the values
#[sub] for a human reader to sanity-check that the walk is producing
#[sub] reasonable numbers for whatever doc is open. Also captures
#[sub] the baseline count to a variable so Phase 8 can do the
#[sub] delta math.

get objects count
set count_before to result

get objects all_iids

#[sub] === Phase 3: SCOPE-NEG — out-of-scope type tokens return "" ===
#[sub] These dispatches run the doc walk but find no in-scope match.
#[sub] Each line emits `= ""` to the trace. Layer / Guide / special-
#[sub] layer types are out of objects scope (option (ii) from the
#[sub] s230 design fork: real scene contents only). An unknown token
#[sub] also returns "" — the vocabulary is fixed.

objects find_by_type "layer"
objects find_by_type "guide"
objects find_by_type "guidelayer"
objects find_by_type "reflayer"
objects find_by_type "measurelayer"
objects find_by_type "gridlayer"
objects find_by_type "marginlayer"
objects find_by_type "nonsense_type_token"

#[sub] find_by_name on a sentinel string that almost certainly
#[sub] doesn't match any user-named object returns "". If somehow
#[sub] the user has an object named this exact string, the trace
#[sub] would show its iid instead of "".

objects find_by_name "__s231_m2_sentinel_no_user_object_uses_this__"

#[sub] === Phase 4: SCOPE-POS — cross-Scriptable boundary assert ===
#[sub] Create an empty test layer. layers.new returns the new
#[sub] layer's iid; bind it to `test_layer`. Rename it to a sentinel
#[sub] so we can find it by name through the `layers` Scriptable.
#[sub] This is the m1-carried foundation assert.

layers new
set test_layer to result
layers.test_layer rename "objects_smoke_test_layer_s231_m2"
layers.test_layer activate

#[sub] Active the test layer specifically — `objects new` adds to
#[sub] the active layer's children, so test objects land somewhere
#[sub] we can target during teardown without disturbing the user's
#[sub] real layers.

#[sub] `layers find_by_name` for the sentinel returns the test
#[sub] layer's iid. Bind the result and round-trip it.

layers find_by_name "objects_smoke_test_layer_s231_m2"
set found_layer to result
assert layers.found_layer name == "objects_smoke_test_layer_s231_m2"

#[sub] `objects find_by_name` for the SAME sentinel returns ""
#[sub] (layers are out of objects' scope). The trace shows `= ""`;
#[sub] no assert because the result-equals-literal shape isn't
#[sub] expressible in today's DSL.

objects find_by_name "objects_smoke_test_layer_s231_m2"

#[sub] === Phase 5: BUILD UP (a) — mint a Path object ===
#[sub] `objects new "path"` creates a fresh empty Path under the
#[sub] active layer (which we just activated above). Returns the new
#[sub] iid into the result slot; `set a to result` binds it for the
#[sub] remainder of the run. The variable holds the iid forever (or
#[sub] until reset()), so even though the Path is going to be deleted
#[sub] in teardown, `a` keeps resolving to the same address — the
#[sub] proxy's resolve() then returns nullptr post-delete.
#[sub]
#[sub] The contract for newly-minted objects: name == "" (the user
#[sub] hasn't named it yet — different from canvas-tool creation
#[sub] which assigns next_default_name). type is the lowercase
#[sub] token matching the requested type. visible default true,
#[sub] locked default false. child_count == 0 (a leaf Path).
#[sub] parent_iid is the active layer's iid (the layer we activated
#[sub] in Phase 4, bound as `found_layer`).

objects new "path"
set a to result

assert objects.a name == ""
assert objects.a type == "path"
assert objects.a visible == true
assert objects.a locked == false
assert objects.a child_count == 0

#[sub] parent_iid round-trip: the iid we bound in `found_layer`
#[sub] should equal objects.a parent_iid. The DSL doesn't have a
#[sub] variable-equality assert (only literal RHS), so we chain
#[sub] through the layers proxy: layers.<a's parent_iid> name
#[sub] should equal the sentinel. If parent_iid returned anything
#[sub] other than the test_layer's iid, this assert would fail
#[sub] (either with a mismatched name, or with an unknown-object
#[sub] error if the bound iid doesn't resolve through `layers`).

get objects.a parent_iid
set a_parent to result
assert layers.a_parent name == "objects_smoke_test_layer_s231_m2"

#[sub] === Phase 5c: ELEMENT MUTATING VERBS on `a` (s232 m3) ===
#[sub] Exercise the five mutating verbs the m3 milestone wires onto
#[sub] ObjectProxy. Each rides EditObjectFieldCommand — a new command
#[sub] class added in m3, a direct analog of EditLayerFieldCommand
#[sub] minus the Color field. Mirrors LayerProxy::invoke's shape
#[sub] exactly; m3 is the "drop the same pattern in a sibling
#[sub] Scriptable" move.
#[sub]
#[sub] We verify three things per field group:
#[sub]   1. The mutating call changes the property.
#[sub]   2. A "no-op same value" call leaves the property unchanged
#[sub]      (the verb body's `before == after` short-circuit; matches
#[sub]      LayerProxy's contract — same value means no command pushed).
#[sub]   3. Cross-check on the iid — for rename, find_by_name on the
#[sub]      new name should resolve back to `a`'s iid (proves rename
#[sub]      propagated into the tree-walk surface, not just the
#[sub]      node-local field).

#[sub] --- rename round-trip ---
#[sub] Mint state was name == "" (the documented sentinel for newly-
#[sub] created objects). Rename it; confirm the name changed; confirm
#[sub] a same-value rename is a no-op (still the new name); confirm
#[sub] an empty-arg rename is a no-op (the rename verb refuses ""
#[sub] arg the same way LayerProxy::rename does).

objects.a rename "renamed_path_alpha"
assert objects.a name == "renamed_path_alpha"

objects.a rename "renamed_path_alpha"
assert objects.a name == "renamed_path_alpha"

objects.a rename ""
assert objects.a name == "renamed_path_alpha"

#[sub] Cross-check via find_by_name: the rename should propagate to
#[sub] the tree-walk surface, not just the node-local field. Binds
#[sub] the iid that find_by_name resolves for the new name; asserts
#[sub] equality against `a` via the variable-RHS substitution
#[sub] grammar (s231 m2 observation: variable-RHS asserts work for
#[sub] any bare_repr-round-trippable type — strings included).

objects find_by_name "renamed_path_alpha"
set found_a to result
assert objects.found_a iid == a

#[sub] --- visible round-trip ---
#[sub] Mint state was visible == true. toggle_visible flips to false;
#[sub] set_visible true flips back; set_visible true (same value)
#[sub] is a no-op.

objects.a toggle_visible
assert objects.a visible == false

objects.a set_visible true
assert objects.a visible == true

objects.a set_visible true
assert objects.a visible == true

#[sub] --- locked round-trip ---
#[sub] Mint state was locked == false. Symmetric to visibility but
#[sub] starts from the opposite bool. toggle_locked flips to true;
#[sub] set_locked false flips back; set_locked false (same value)
#[sub] is a no-op.

objects.a toggle_locked
assert objects.a locked == true

objects.a set_locked false
assert objects.a locked == false

objects.a set_locked false
assert objects.a locked == false

#[sub] === Phase 6: BUILD UP (b) — mint a Group object ===
#[sub] Second test object, different type. Confirms the type
#[sub] discriminator works (path vs group) and the iid-collision
#[sub] check holds (a and b have distinct iids — if `objects new`
#[sub] minted the same iid twice we'd see name issues because the
#[sub] proxy lookup would resolve to whichever node was first in
#[sub] tree-walk order). Also confirms a Group's child_count is 0
#[sub] when freshly minted (the children vector is default-empty).

objects new "group"
set b to result

assert objects.b type == "group"
assert objects.b child_count == 0

#[sub] === Phase 6c: ELEMENT MUTATING VERBS on `b` (s232 m3) ===
#[sub] Minimal smoke that the verbs work on Group-typed nodes too,
#[sub] not just Path. The five verbs are type-agnostic (they edit
#[sub] SceneNode::name / visible / locked, which are uniform across
#[sub] every node type), but a cheap re-exercise on a different type
#[sub] confirms there's no type-gated branch hiding in the code path.
#[sub] One verb per field group is enough; the deeper round-trip
#[sub] coverage lives in Phase 5c.

objects.b rename "renamed_group_beta"
assert objects.b name == "renamed_group_beta"

objects.b toggle_locked
assert objects.b locked == true

#[sub] === Phase 7: find_by_type — now finds in-scope objects ===
#[sub] With a Path and a Group under the test layer, the previously
#[sub] empty find_by_type "path" / "group" calls now return iids.
#[sub] Round-trip the returned iid through the proxy and assert on
#[sub] type — same chain pattern as Phase 5's parent_iid check.
#[sub]
#[sub] Note: find_by_type's contract is "first hit in walk order."
#[sub] If the user already has paths/groups in their doc, the iid
#[sub] returned is whichever appears FIRST in the tree walk — that's
#[sub] not necessarily our `a` or `b`. But the type-token contract
#[sub] still holds: WHATEVER iid comes back resolves to a node
#[sub] whose type matches the query. So we assert on type, not on
#[sub] iid identity.

objects find_by_type "path"
set found_path to result
assert objects.found_path type == "path"

objects find_by_type "group"
set found_group to result
assert objects.found_group type == "group"

#[sub] === Phase 8: COUNT DELTA — through mint, before tear down ===
#[sub] We minted 2 objects. count should now be count_before + 2.
#[sub] The DSL's literal-RHS assert can't do arithmetic, but we can
#[sub] capture count_after_mint and the post-teardown count, then
#[sub] confirm that the pre and post counts match — the round-trip
#[sub] over (mint, mint, delete, delete) is a no-op on count.

get objects count
set count_after_mint to result

#[sub] === Phase 9: POST-MINT — cross-Scriptable partition still holds ===
#[sub] After populating `objects` with two real members, re-run the
#[sub] cross-Scriptable boundary check from Phase 4. The previously
#[sub] empty answer for `objects find_by_name <layer_sentinel>` should
#[sub] STILL be empty — `objects` doesn't see layer-typed nodes
#[sub] regardless of how populated the in-scope set is. The layers
#[sub] side should still find the test layer.

assert layers.found_layer name == "objects_smoke_test_layer_s231_m2"

objects find_by_name "objects_smoke_test_layer_s231_m2"

#[sub] === Phase 10: TEAR DOWN ===
#[sub] Delete b first, then a (LIFO over the mint order — matches
#[sub] how a user's undo stack would pop them). Then delete the
#[sub] test_layer. Net structural state on the doc is identical to
#[sub] the pre-run state; net side effect is an AddNodeCommand /
#[sub] DeleteObjectCommand pair per object, plus the layer pair, on
#[sub] the undo stack.

objects delete b
objects delete a
layers delete test_layer

#[sub] count should now match count_before — we minted 2 and
#[sub] deleted 2. The literal-RHS assert can't say "count ==
#[sub] count_before"; we bind both and rely on the substitution
#[sub] grammar — `assert <object> <property> == <var>` resolves
#[sub] <var> to the bound text value BEFORE comparison. count is an
#[sub] integer, count_before is an integer captured at Phase 2. The
#[sub] equality is integer-typed.

get objects count
set count_after_delete to result
assert objects count == count_before

#[sub] We also have count_after_mint bound but don't assert on it
#[sub] (no expression-on-RHS in the DSL). The TRACE will show the
#[sub] three counts side-by-side for a human reader to confirm the
#[sub] +2 / -2 arithmetic:
#[sub]   count_before        — baseline
#[sub]   count_after_mint    — baseline + 2 (paths and groups added)
#[sub]   count_after_delete  — baseline (back to start)

#[sub] === Final list — registry sanity ===
#[sub] `objects` is still registered. No transient `objects.<iid>`
#[sub] entries appear despite the dozens of proxy materialisations
#[sub] across this run. Variables (a, b, count_before, etc.) don't
#[sub] register either — listener-local, not registry entries.

list

#[sub] Done. The s232 m3 surface is validated end-to-end:
#[sub]
#[sub]   - Read side from m1 still works (Phases 1-4, carried).
#[sub]   - `objects new "path"` mints a Path leaf with the documented
#[sub]     empty-name / default-state contract (Phase 5).
#[sub]   - All five element mutating verbs work on the proxy: rename,
#[sub]     toggle_visible, set_visible, toggle_locked, set_locked.
#[sub]     Same-value calls are no-ops (no command pushed); empty-arg
#[sub]     rename is a no-op. rename propagates to the find_by_name
#[sub]     tree-walk surface, not just the node-local field
#[sub]     (Phase 5c).
#[sub]   - `objects new "group"` mints a Group container with the
#[sub]     same default state, distinguishable by type token
#[sub]     (Phase 6).
#[sub]   - Mutating verbs are type-agnostic — they work on Group-
#[sub]     typed nodes the same as Path-typed ones (Phase 6c).
#[sub]   - find_by_type now returns non-empty for in-scope tokens
#[sub]     and the returned iid round-trips through the proxy to a
#[sub]     node of the expected type (Phase 7).
#[sub]   - The count walks correctly across mint and delete cycles —
#[sub]     baseline-2-baseline round trip (Phases 8, 10).
#[sub]   - The cross-Scriptable partition holds even with `objects`
#[sub]     populated (Phase 9).
#[sub]   - `objects delete <iid>` removes nodes from any owning
#[sub]     container in the doc, undoing cleanly via the pushed
#[sub]     DeleteObjectCommand (Phase 10; the trace's `ok` lines
#[sub]     are the dispatch confirmation).
#[sub]
#[sub] Pre-stated: 25 pass / 0 fail / 0 error.
#[sub]
#[sub] What's still NOT covered by m3 (and that's by design):
#[sub]   - Element structural verbs (move, reparent, duplicate).
#[sub]     Scheduled m4.
#[sub]   - Collection-level grouping verbs (group, ungroup).
#[sub]     Scheduled m5.
#[sub]   - selected_iids. Scheduled with the `selection` singleton.
#[sub]   - The find_by_name cross-check assert (Phase 5c) is the
#[sub]     only test that rename propagates to the tree-walk surface;
#[sub]     toggle_visible / toggle_locked don't have an analogous
#[sub]     cross-check because no `find_by_visible` / `find_by_locked`
#[sub]     verb exists (and per CANON's "row-bound model Scriptables"
#[sub]     section, none is planned — visibility and lock state are
#[sub]     mutable display flags, not addressing keys).
